Our approach to this multi-task problem of detecting precipitation, precipitation type and visibility (fog) is a smart sensor, WeathercAIm, consisting of a combination of a camera with edge artificial intelligence (AI) computer vision (CV) processing. This smart sensor is part of the ICSSN and processes the camera images locally.
The proposed design of WeathercAIm is a camera connected to the ICSSN that also runs the precipitation type and visibility AI model.
For the machine learning (ML) model, a supervised learning approach is used for multiclass classification, using a classifier based on a CNN that has proven its merits in the computer vision field.
An initial model was trained on a public dataset, Adverse Weather Dataset (AWD), to evaluate the feasibility of detecting the mentioned weather parameters. The dataset contained most but not all weather classes of interest for SARWS and had a good balance between the classes.
We use a single CNN handling both precipitation type and visibility detection. The current implementation is a CNN with a ResNet50v2 backbone and a dense layer as classification head. The CNN is trained via transfer learning with fine-tuning, with the backbone network pre-trained on ImageNet. Cross-entropy is used as a loss function with stochastic gradient descent (SGD) as an optimizer. To counter overfitting, image augmentation, i.e. rotation, horizontal flip, translation, zoom and contrast, regularization and dropout layers are used. The CNN model is implemented in Keras/TensorFlow.
With this model we achieved good scores, with accuracy, F1, AUC all in the high 90%, indicating that WeathercAIm CNN can learn the weather classes with a good accuracy based on the given dataset.
This initial model was also deployed in ICSSN for the field test.
Initial results from the field test revealed that there is still room for improvement in accuracy on real life production data.
Some observations during the field test:
●	the resolution of the camera does not allow for a high performance in changing lighting conditions, producing lesser quality images than the camera images from the AWD dataset
●	different environmental setting, e.g. camera placement, urban scenes and weather conditions compared to AWD dataset, which were taken in Canada.
●	special (non-weather) cases encountered in real-life like tunnels, vehicle in garage, etc.
To improve WeathercAIm to suit the actual field production conditions, a more data centric approach is followed.

This is particularly important for startups that are still in the early stages of development and may not yet have a proven business model. Radiation-induced myocardial fibrosis (RIMF) is a potentially severe lethal clinical complication after chest radiotherapy (RT), which is the major common denominator of radiation-induced heart disease (RIHD). RIMF is characterized by decreased ventricular elasticity and distensibility, resulting in decreased ejection fraction and heart failure, and even sudden cardiac death, which impairs the long-term health of post-RT survivors and limits dose and intensity of RT required to effectively kill tumor cells. Although the exact mechanisms involving in RIMF are not clear, overwhelming evidence indicates that the occurrence of RIMF is related to various cells, regulatory molecules, and cytokines. And accurately diagnosing and identifying patients who may progress to RIMF is challenging. Despite the urgent need for an effective treatment, there is no medical therapy for RIMF approved for routine clinical application. In this review, we have focused on the underlying pathophysiology that is critically involved in the initiation and progression of RIMF and then outlined potential preventative and therapeutic strategies to counter this toxicity, providing a basis for therapeutic strategies of RIMF.

Paragraph: Persons with sleep apnea syndromes experience 10 or more episodes per hour of sleep during which airflow ceases for more than 10 seconds. Sleep apnea syndromes are classified as obstructive, central or mixed: obstructive when the respiratory muscles continue to contract but airflow is not obtained, central when respiratory effort is not present, and mixed when elements of both obstructive and central apnea are present. Approximately 4 percent of adult men and 2 percent of adult women are believed to have these conditions. In addition to having symptoms such as snoring, headaches, depression, decreased libido and fatigue, patients with sleep apnea are at risk for a range of severe complications secondary to recurrent hypoxia and hypercapnia during sleep. Diagnosis may require an overnight polysomnogram in addition to the history, a physical examination and a laboratory assessment. Less cumbersome diagnostic modalities are being developed. Treatment options include weight reduction, change in sleeping position, avoidance of sedatives, use of continuous positive airway pressure and surgical treatment
